nodes.bodyText:
I didn't do performance tests, but optimistic concurrency is usually faster than lock-based concurrency, if the platform supports the atomic compare-and-set.
If the platform supports the atomic compare-and-set, then I'd guess this isn't much slower than non-concurrent case. If the platform doesn't support atomic compare-and-set, then it would likely be implemented using locks and would have the same performance as the lock-based implementation.
The do-while equivalent of this is:
        int currentCapacity;
        int newCapacity;
        do {
            currentCapacity = capacity.get();

            if (currentCapacity == maxCapacity) {
                return;
            }

            newCapacity = Math.min(currentCapacity + amountToRelease, maxCapacity);
        } while (!capacity.compareAndSet(currentCapacity, newCapacity));
... if it makes it less scary. I feel like the current writing is a little more straight-foward, though. We can walk through the code on chime if that would help make it less scary.
The current implementation will almost always iterate just once, because the value is unlikely to be changed between currentCapacity = capacity.get() and capacity.compareAndSet(currentCapacity, newCapacity).

